supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil (in lower left corner on folios with full-page miniatures), 1-137. Some folio numbers appear to have been corrected.

p.note: Top of page, in black ink by an ealy modern hand: Drottningholms Bibl. Kat. no 96; below, in the same hand, the date 8/20 1854. Centre of page, in black ink by a different early modern hand, a tally of the ornamental elements: 136 skrifna blad 15 taflor med hela ramar och stora initialer 10 mindre ramstycken och 10 initialer 182 mindre initialer 826 små initialer 62 små rankor. Bottom of page, in pencil by a modern hand: Tillhör KB.

binding.p: 18th-century binding. Red leather over cardboard. 4 double raised bands and endbands. , stamped in gold at the centre: the coat of arms of Queen Lovisa Ulrika of Sweden. , stamped in gold: MANUSCRIPT; below, A 232.

history.origin: France , Clermont , 15th century, second half. The inclusion in the calendar of the feast of the Transfiguration (), instituted in 1457, gives a terminus post quem for the date of the manuscript. The inclusion of a large number of bishops, prelates, and martyrs of Clermont (e.g. Austremonius, Antholianus, Trigidius, Bonitus, Genesius, as well as Agricola and Vitalis) points to this as the place of origin. A former librarian notes, however, that the miniatures are of Flemish style.
history.provenance: The manuscript belonged to Lovisa Ulrika, Queen of Sweden 1751-1771 (her coat of arms on ). No 96 in the library catalogue of Drottningholm Palace.
history.acquisition: Transferred to the Royal Library in .

note.p: : translation of St William of Bourges (7 May);
: translation of Agricola and Vitalis (27 Nov.);
: the ascender of the d in Benedicti is embellished with a scroll.
St Romanus is placed on August 8 rather than 9, and for the remainder of August, the feasts are early by one day (or two) compared to the common dates.
